<subSubSection pageId="96" pageNumber="492" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="96.[778,1371,886,1313]" pageId="96" pageNumber="492">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[778,1028,1201,1234]" pageId="96" pageNumber="492">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 65-86 mm, tail 65-88 mm, hindfoot 14-16 mm. No specific data are available for body weight.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="96.[163,1370,1319,2061]" pageId="96" pageNumber="492">
Condylo-incisive lengths are 19-9-22-2 mm, and tooth rows are 8:6-9-8 mm. Cranbrook’s White-toothed Shrew is medium-sized and intermediate in size between the larger Southeast Asian White-toothed Shrew (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Blyth" baseAuthorityYear="1855" box="[806,971,1398,1431]" class="Mammalia" family="Soricidae" genus="Crocidura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="96" pageNumber="484" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fuliginosa">C. fuliginosa</taxonomicName>
) and the smaller Asian Gray White-toothed Shrew (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Milne-Edwards" authorityYear="1872" box="[503,679,1438,1471]" class="Mammalia" family="Soricidae" genus="Crocidura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="96" pageNumber="498" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="attenuata">C. attenuata</taxonomicName>
). Dorsal pelage of Cranbrook’s White-toothed Shrew is brown, and ventral pelage is paler, dark gray-brown. Hands and feet are light buff. Tail is long, thin, and 81-108% of head-body length. Bristle hairs occur on proximal 30% oftail. Rostrum is long, and zygomatic plate is broad. Braincase is long and low. I' has large principal cusp. M? is large, with bicuspid mesostyle and broad talon.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="96" pageNumber="492" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="96.[163,1370,1319,2061]" pageId="96" pageNumber="492">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[165,276,1634,1667]" pageId="96" pageNumber="492">Habitat.</emphasis>
High river valleys and surrounding hills, with temperate broadleaf and mixed forests and tropical and subtropical moist broadleaf forests at elevations of915-1220 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[165,1147,1713,1746]" pageId="96" pageNumber="492" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph blockId="96.[163,1370,1319,2061]" box="[165,1147,1713,1746]" pageId="96" pageNumber="492">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[165,427,1713,1746]" pageId="96" pageNumber="492">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
Cranbrook’s White-toothed Shrew is insectivorous.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[165,538,1752,1785]" pageId="96" pageNumber="492" type="breeding">
<paragraph blockId="96.[163,1370,1319,2061]" box="[165,538,1752,1785]" pageId="96" pageNumber="492">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[165,299,1752,1785]" pageId="96" pageNumber="492">Breeding.</emphasis>
